quiz.title: Algorithmic Problem Solving Quiz
quiz.description:
It's time to check your knowledge! Use this quiz to create a custom study guide. Note any answers that were marked incorrect, so you can study the relevant material and try this quiz again.

If you don't know the answer to a question, please do not guess. Instead, select "I don't know". It's OK not to know everything and to admit when we're unsure.

questions.question_text:
A/an _____ is simply a well-defined procedure, or set of instructions, for
accomplishing a specific task.

_____ is used to classify algorithms according to how their run time or
space requirements grow as the input size grows.

Calculate the time complexity for the following code using Big O notation:

function logLetter(string) {
  for (const letter of string) {
    console.log(letter);
  }
}

answers.comments: Correct! Since the algorithm needs to iterate through each letter of the input, the time complexity will grow in linear proportion to the size of the input.
answers.comments_html:
Correct! Since the algorithm needs to iterate through each letter of the input,
the time complexity will grow in linear proportion to the size of the input.

answers.comments: Not quite. O(1) would mean the algorithm's runtime stays the same regardless of how large the input is.
answers.comments_html:
Not quite. O(1) would mean the algorithm's runtime stays the same regardless of
how large the input is.

answers.comments: Not quite. O(n²) would mean the algorithm's runtime grows exponentially as the size of the input grows, like an algorithm that involved a nested loop.
answers.comments_html:
Not quite. O(n²) would mean the algorithm's runtime grows exponentially as the
size of the input grows, like an algorithm that involved a nested loop.

answers.comments: Not quite. O(log n) would mean that the algorithm's time complexity grows in a logarithmic proportion to the size of the input (so an input of size 1 would take 1 step, size 10 would take 2 steps, size 100 would take 3 steps, etc).
answers.comments_html:
Not quite. O(log n) would mean that the algorithm's time complexity grows in a
logarithmic proportion to the size of the input (so an input of size 1 would
take 1 step, size 10 would take 2 steps, size 100 would take 3 steps, etc).

answers.comments: Be sure to study the source/s for this question. You'll get it next time.

questions.question_text:
Calculate the time complexity for the following code using Big O notation:

function badCounting(array) {
  let count = 0;
  array.forEach((value, idx) => {
    array.forEach((testValue, testIdx) => {
      if (testIdx !== idx && value === testValue) {
        count++;
      }
    });
  });
  return count / 2;
}

answers.comments: Correct! Since this algorithm comparing each element against each other element in this array, as the size of the input array grows, the runtime gets exponentially worse.
answers.comments_html:
Correct! Since this algorithm comparing each element against each other element
in this array, as the size of the input array grows, the runtime gets
exponentially worse.

answers.comments: Now quite. O(n) would mean the time complexity will grow in linear proportion to the size of the input.

the size of the input.

how large the input is.

questions.question_text:
Calculate the time complexity for the following code using Big O notation:

function findIndexOfElement(array, target) {
  return array.indexOf(target);
}

answers.comments: Correct! Even though we're building a built-in method, the JavaScript engine would still need to iterate over every element of the input array under the hood in order to find the index position of the target element.
